      ],
      "name": "Myceloid",
      "sections": [
        {
          "image": {
            "image": "Sidebar_2_AdditionalLore.png",
            "name": "Additional Lore",
            "type": "image"
          },
          "name": "Table Manners",
          "sidebar_heading": "Additional Lore",
          "sidebar_type": "additional_lore",
          "sources": [
            {
              "link": {
                "alt": "Monster Core 2 pg. 231",
                "aonid": 276,
                "game-obj": "Sources",
                "name": "Monster Core 2 pg. 231",
                "type": "link"
              },
              "name": "Monster Core 2",
              "page": 231,
              "type": "source"
            }
          ],
          "subtype": "sidebar",
          "text": "Myceloids eat communal meals consisting of a series of corpses, beginning with creatures they killed in combat, followed by any that died in service while controlled by Spore Domination. As they dine, they offer tasting notes, claiming they can taste intangibles like innocence or despair. They save any creature that died from purple pox as dessert. The new myceloid birthed from the corpse gets the first slice!",
          "type": "section"
        }
      ],
      "sources": [
        {
          "link": {
            "alt": "Monster Core 2 pg. 231",
            "aonid": 276,
            "game-obj": "Sources",
            "name": "Monster Core 2 pg. 231",
            "type": "link"
          },
          "name": "Monster Core 2",
          "page": 231,
          "type": "source"
        }
      ],
      "text": "The ambulatory fungus creatures called myceloids are notorious for spreading deadly purple pox, controlling creatures' minds, and devouring humanoid flesh. For a myceloid colony, any battle with humanoids is cause for excitement, as this new fodder presents so many delicious and satisfying possibilities.  \n  \nMyceloids consider humanoids to have an ideal life cycle of four simple steps. During childhood, they wander naive and afraid, unaware of myceloid colonies. In adulthood, humanoids discover their true purpose as they taste purple pox and become controlled by the myceloids' spores. Next, they die, giving rise to a new myceloid. They're then sent on to the afterlife upon becoming a myceloid meal. Eating humanoid flesh isn't a necessity\u2014a myceloid can survive on any decaying matter\u2014but it's certainly their favored fare. Myceloids rarely make alliances, but when they do, they invite their new allies to share a meal to seal the pact. Few outsiders appreciate this hospitality.  \n  \nMost myceloids have deep purple caps studded with off-white lumps.   \n  \nTheir necks and bodies bear resemblance to the stipes of tough, leathery fungi. Smaller mushrooms often grow on a myceloid's body, which the creatures view as either adornments or particularly convenient snacks. They stand roughly as tall as dwarves, with comparably stout builds.",
      "type": "section"
    }
  ],
